Fed officials to discuss the need to taper. Since the summer, however, he became much more dovish, highlighting concerns about the too low inflation rate. Today’s remarks suggest that Mr Bullard has again abandoned his dovish bias and is – under certain conditions – willing to support the tapering.</p> <p>In short, his speech and the presented slides indicate that to him average monthly payroll gains of about 180,000 would represent a substantial improvement in the labor market, the necessary condition for the Fed to wind-down its asset purchase program.</p> </blockquote> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-11-01T16:34:44.267Z\">at 4.34pm GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-5273bd15e4b0ad7c52b60506\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-01T14:51:23.990Z\">2.51pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-54f4114c-24a0-4fae-80d6-6e17e4da06cf\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Lifeandhealth/Pix/pictures/2013/8/22/1377166412900/Shopper-pushes-a-trolley--010.jpg\" alt=\"Ikea founder Ingvar Kamprad is 412th on the Forbes list of billionaires. David Sillitoe for the Guardian\" width=\"460\" height=\"276\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>David Sillitoe for the Guardian</figcaption> </figure> <p>Here is a question for Friday afternoon:<strong> why does Sweden have so many billionaires?&nbsp;</strong><strong>Matthew Yglesias&nbsp;</strong>at&nbsp;<strong>Slate </strong>looks at&nbsp;why a country famed for its generous welfare state, produces such a high number of super rich individuals, relative to its population size.</p> <p>Critics of the Swedish model have contended that state spending is a barrier to innovation, a myth that Yglesias debunks.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>To reach that level of stratospheric riches, you probably either need to start a big, successful company or else inherit one from someone who did. And however much people care about inequality, almost every place on Earth would like to be the kind of place where successful new firms are born and raised.</p> <p>The good news about Sweden is that it’s exactly that kind of place. High taxes go to finance cheap health care and education, an excellent system of public transportation, and relatively generous subsidies to low-income households that keep the poverty rate and inequality low. But they haven’t stopped Swedish entrepreneurs from building giant firms like H&amp;M, Ikea, and&nbsp;Tetra Pak.</p> </blockquote> <p>You can read his full piece <a href=\"http://www.slate.com/articles/business/billion_to_one/2013/10/sweden_s_billionaires_they_have_more_per_capita_than_the_united_states.html\">here</a>.</p> <p><em>I am passing onto Nick Fletcher now. Thanks for all the comments so far...</em></p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-11-01T15:03:43.128Z\">at 3.03pm GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-5273ba8ae4b0020e1b71994b\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-01T14:34:24.271Z\">2.34pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">A different view on US manufacturing output</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>Data firm Markit also keeps an eye on U.S factory output. Using a slightly different methodology, they paint a gloomier picture than the ISM.</p> <p>The <strong>Markit manufacturing purchasing managers index</strong> stood at 51.8 in October, better than expected, but still a point below September's reading. As usual, 50 counts for expansion.</p> <p><strong>Chris Williamson, </strong>chief economist at<strong> Markit, </strong>said October's troubles could be temporary.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>However, even the faster growth of employment remains only modest, consistent with barely any increase in official data on manufacturing payrolls.</p> </blockquote> <p>So there you are.</p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-11-01T14:35:35.158Z\">at 2.35pm GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-5273b6fae4b0ad7c52b60504\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-01T14:23:13.722Z\">2.23pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">U.S manufacturers ignored shutdown</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>The U.S manufacturing data is compiled by the <strong>Institute for Supply Management</strong> and you can crunch through their full data <a href=\"http://www.ism.ws/news/newsreleasedetail.cfm?ItemNumber=23964\">here</a>.</p> <p><strong>A few highlights:</strong></p> <p>•14 out of 18 manufacturing sectors recorded growth in October</p> <p>• New orders were slightly up on the previous month: 60.6 Oct v 60.5 in Sept</p> <p>•Production was also down: 60.8 Oct v 62.6 Sept</p> <p>•Employment showed the weakest growth since June: 53.2 in Oct v 55.4 in Sept</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-5273b591e4b0be3ac2bf4ae2\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-01T14:09:43.632Z\">2.09pm <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>The instant view:</p> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/bencasselman/statuses/396276031016800256\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>Strongest PMI since April 2011. It's almost as though factory owners don't make long-term decisions based on short-term political turmoil.</p>— Ben Casselman (@bencasselman) <a href=\"https://twitter.com/bencasselman/statuses/396276031016800256\">November 1, 2013</a></blockquote> </figure> <figure class=\"element element-tweet\" data-canonical-url=\"https://twitter.com/NeilShahWSJ/statuses/396277200887902209\"> <blockquote class=\"twitter-tweet\"><p>So much for the government shutdown snuffing out US factory output. ISM PMI g