 asked when the British taxpayer would get their money back from<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2011/dec/12/rbs-collapse-timeline\"> bailing out the Royal Bank of Scotland</a>.</p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>I think, sadly, it is still some way off.</p> <p>I think, quite frankly, it is unlikely before the general election.&nbsp;</p> <p>If there was a transformation in RBS and all these problems that it has to confront were dealt with much more quickly, maybe we would reconsider. But I say 'unlikely' in the real sense of the word, which is I don't think it's very likely.</p> <p>I wouldn't feel comfortable going to the British people and saying 'Invest in RBS' until I was absolutely clear that it was on top of its problems.</p> </blockquote> <p>Quotes courtesy of PA</p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-11-01T09:04:43.675Z\">at 9.04am GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-52736409e4b0ad7c52b604de\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-01T08:31:27.512Z\">8.31am <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">RBS warns of heavy losses</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>The <strong>Royal Bank of Scotland</strong> is on course to make a substantial loss in 2013, its chief executive has said this morning, as it announced it would create a mini bad bank to house its toxic assets.</p> <p>RBS shares are down 3.4%, making them the biggest faller on the FTSE 100, and at 355 pence well below the 500 pence the taxpayer paid for them when the bank received its bailout.</p> <p>Here is the report from the Guardian's city editor <strong>Jill Treanor</strong></p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>The review into creating a bad bank –&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/jun/19/osborne-lloyds-rbs-sell-off\">commissioned by the chancellor George Osborne after the Mansion House speech in June</a>&nbsp;– had concluded the &quot;effort, risk and expense involved in the creation of an external bad bank is not justified&quot;.</p> <p>Instead about &pound;38bn of troublesome loans – including &pound;9bn from Ulster Bank – will be placed into a new non-core division to be known as the capital resolution division, which will aims to be wound down in two years.</p> <p>McEwan – who said he wanted to &quot;reset the key relationships&quot; with government and regulators – will accelerate the spin off RBS's US arm Citizens to next year rather than 2015 and signalled a review of a large number of businesses, the outcome of which will be announced in February.</p> </blockquote> <p>You can read the full story <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/nov/01/royal-bank-scotland-losses-internal-bad-bank-rbs\">here</a>.</p> </div> <p class=\"block-time updated-time\">Updated <time datetime=\"2013-11-01T08:34:02.744Z\">at 8.34am GMT</time></p> </div> <div id=\"block-5273633ce4b01fc33230d437\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-01T08:17:37.446Z\">8.17am <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>It is the electronic equivalent of 'leaves on the line'... we are doing some technical work on our blog platforms and no comments can be posted at the moment. I'll post an update when I have more information.</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-527360a8e4b0be3ac2bf4ace\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-01T08:15:48.898Z\">8.15am <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <h2 class=\"block-title\">European markets open flat</h2> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p>European markets are looking subdued this morning, on a day that is a public holiday in several countries.</p> <p>FTSE 100 +0.24% at 6,747 points</p> <p>Spain's IBEX -0.2% at 9,888 points</p> <p>Italy's FTSE MIB -0.5% at 19,237 points</p> </div> </div> <div id=\"block-52735d03e4b01fc33230d436\" class=\"block\"> <p class=\"block-time published-time\"> <time datetime=\"2013-11-01T08:02:50.095Z\">8.02am <span class=\"timezone\">GMT</span></time> </p> <div class=\"block-elements\"> <p><strong>Good morning, and welcome to our rolling coverage of the world economy, the financial markets, the eurozone and the business world.</strong></p> <p>China’s manufacturing sector grew at its fastest pace in 18 months, adding to signs that the world’s second largest economy is stabilising.</p> <p>The official purchasing managers’ survey rose to 51.4 from 51.1 - an index where anything over 50 means growth. Analysts now think China could exceed its 7.5% growth target this year. A separate HSBC survey also showed that manufacturing was expanding.</p> <p>And we have plenty of other news. The Royal Bank of Scotland has just announced &pound;634m loss for the third quarter, as it outlines plans to create an internal ‘bad bank’ for its problem loans.&nbsp;Germany has hit back at US criticism of its export-focused economic policy - adding to tensions between the two countries over spying.</p> <p>UK data released at 9.30 is expected to show expansion in the manufacturing sector, although slightly below last month.</p> <p>I’ll be tracking that and all the latest throughout the day...</p> </div> </div><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/421434452|2013-11-01T16:42:45Z|26078e8b683b559bc7c2d30273af7125b136fdae -->",
