      "id":"business/marketforceslive/2013/nov/01/meggitt-royal-bank-scotland-ftse-federal-reserve",
      "sectionId":"business",
      "sectionName":"Business",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-11-01T09:29:48Z",
      "webTitle":"Meggitt drops after it downgrades revenues while RBS falls after figures",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/business/marketforceslive/2013/nov/01/meggitt-royal-bank-scotland-ftse-federal-reserve",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/business/marketforceslive/2013/nov/01/meggitt-royal-bank-scotland-ftse-federal-reserve",
      "fields":{
        "trailText":"Investors cautious over Federal Reserve tapering, while aircraft parts maker disappoints",
        "headline":"Meggitt drops after it downgrades revenues while RBS falls after figures",
        "body":"<p>With <strong>Royal Bank of Scotland</strong> reporting <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/nov/01/royal-bank-scotland-losses-internal-bad-bank-rbs\" title=\"\">a hefty third quarter loss of more than £600m</a>, it takes some doing to be the recipient of the market's wooden spoon.</p><p>But aircraft parts supplier <strong>Meggitt</strong> has done it, falling more than 8% to 525.5p to make it the biggest faller in the FTSE 100. Meggitt said it expected revenues to grow in the low single digits this year, down from its prediction in August of mid-single digit gains.</p><p>The company, which makes avionics and wheels for the likes of Airbus and Boeing, said trading in the four months to the middle of October had fallen slightly below expectations. It said:</p><p><blockquote>[This was] principally due to short term production difficulties at Meggitt Sensing Systems and the timing of contract wins and project milestones in one of our energy businesses.</blockquote></p><p></p><p>It said military revenues remained flat despite the US budget issues, but the strengthening of the pound against the dollar in the second half also had an effect. But it identified a raw material supply issue dating back to 2012, involving replacing various parts over the next few years at a cost of £20m. Analyst Chris Dyett at Investec said:</p><p><blockquote>Meggitt's third quarter management statement is a disappointment, leading us to make pretax profit downgrades of around 7% for this year and next. Underlying trading is largely as expected, but a number of newly identified issues have impacted the second half and also 2014. In addition, a foreign exchange headwind has compounded the issues. Our new price target is 515p and we move to hold, expecting the stock to unwind part of the recent re-rating as well as reflecting the downgrade.<br /><br /></blockquote></p><p>RBS meanwhile is indeed down after its figures, the second biggest faller after Meggitt with a 12.9p or 3.5% decline to 354.7p. Barclays is also lower, down 7.75p at 255.85p. Both banks are among those being sued by US group Fannie Mae over the libor scandal.</p><p>Overall the <strong>FTSE 100</strong> is down 11.36 points at 6720.07 as investors continue to be concerned about the US Federal Reserve easing its bond buying programme after some recent upbeat data, albeit the central bank made no changes at its meeting earlier this week.</p><p>Better than expected Chinese PMI figures failed to lift the mining sector, with <strong>Rio Tinto</strong> down 4.5p at 3153.5p. Fears of Fed tapering outweighed the positive signs from China.</p><p>But <strong>Vodafone</strong> jumped 4.65p to 229.15p on renewed talk of possible bid interest from US group AT&amp;T, in the wake of the UK mobile group's sale of its stake in its American wireless joint venture to partner Verizon.</p><p><strong>Royal Dutch Shell</strong> B shares have recovered 12.5p to £20.89 in the wake of Thursday's disappointing figures, while <strong>BG</strong> has added 8p to 1281.5p.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/421441247|2013-11-01T16:42:45Z|fc5ab4232609fe27cc4f820816b817cee18dd782 -->",
