      "id":"business/2013/nov/01/rbs-business-lending-attacked",
      "sectionId":"business",
      "sectionName":"Business",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-11-01T07:32:00Z",
      "webTitle":"RBS fails to lend to small firms, says former Bank of England official",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/nov/01/rbs-business-lending-attacked",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/business/2013/nov/01/rbs-business-lending-attacked",
      "fields":{
        "trailText":"Royal Bank of Scotland has been over-cautious about lending to SME sector, says report",
        "headline":"RBS fails to lend to small firms, says former Bank of England official",
        "body":"<p>Royal Bank of Scotland received stinging criticism on Friday for turning away too many small business customers as a result of overly strict lending criteria and a complex management structure.</p><p>The 81% taxpayer-owned bank failed to meet its own goals for lending to small businesses – regarded as a potential engine of growth for the economy – and has been too aggressive towards existing customers facing financial difficulty, according to the report by Sir Andrew Large, a former deputy governor of the Bank of England.</p><p>Outlining nine recommendations, Large suggests the bank conduct a forensic inquiry into the way it has treated customers in distress. He also says it should  create more coherent and realistic targets for lending to the small and medium-size enterprise (SME) sector.</p><p>Ross McEwan, presenting his first set of results since being promoted to chief executive, said: \"The picture Sir Andrew Large paints is not an entirely comfortable one, but it's one we have to confront. A successful, vibrant and well-regarded SME bank is central to the overall value and reputation of this company.\"</p><p>McEwan said he was conducting a review of the bank and would report back in February. In the meantime the bank is to write to customers and speed up the time it takes to grant loans after Large said the bank should give staff more confidence to lend.</p><p>Large said one person should be put in charge of the SME business, which is currently split across the business bank, the non-core division, the 315 branches that must be sold off to meet EU rules and a division  which looks after financially stretched customers.</p><p>The bank has faced repeated criticism over its lending to SMEs. The report said RBS had been losing market share – from 42% of net lending in the months before its 2008 bailout to 27% five years later – after reducing the period of time over which it was prepared to lend. It added that \"risk aversion\" among its bankers meant credit-worthy customers were turned away.</p><p>The report, commissioned by the bank following repeated criticism from politicians and small businesses bosses, said RBS's stock of lending has continued to fall this year, by £1.8bn in the first half, when rivals were expanding their SME lending.</p><p>\"RBS should look afresh at the manner in which it delivers lending to SMEs and make sure that the various components of its offering to customers are aligned,\" said Large.</p><p>RBS's lending before the 2008 crash was unsustainable when it reached £55bn but it then fell too quickly to £38bn. The bank had been trying to reduce its exposure to commercial property lending but as a result had turned away creditworthy customers.</p><p>\"The bank failed to meet its own SME lending targets, partly because they were unrealistic and also because of weakness in its lending operations,\" Large said.</p><p>Until 2012, the RBS small business bankers had been focused on gathering deposits and worrying about risk rather than issuing new loans. The processes inside the bank meant that credit controllers were turning away applications too quickly.</p><p>The report said RBS had been more active than its rivals in renegotiating loans after the crisis. \"RBS has also changed the way it manages its relationship with customers that it believes have shown signs of financial deterioration or distress. A small minority of customers who have experienced this have made serious allegations about the actions that RBS has taken,\" the report said.</p><p>The inquiry needed to substantiate or refute these allegations, the report said.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/421424810|2013-11-01T16:42:45Z|5f018c5765a0d76f9b564ef1bd96476cbcfb1601 -->",
