      "id":"money/2013/oct/31/george-osborne-capital-gains-tax-overseas-buyers",
      "sectionId":"money",
      "sectionName":"Money",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-31T11:39:04Z",
      "webTitle":"George Osborne 'considers capital gains tax for overseas buyers'",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/money/2013/oct/31/george-osborne-capital-gains-tax-overseas-buyers",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/money/2013/oct/31/george-osborne-capital-gains-tax-overseas-buyers",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"28",
        "trailText":"Sky News says the chancellor may impose CGT, currently only paid by UK citizens, on foreign buyers selling UK property",
        "headline":"George Osborne 'considers capital gains tax for overseas buyers'",
        "body":"<p>The government is reported to be considering a tax for overseas investors buying UK properties, in a move to stop house prices rushing out of reach of homebuyers.</p><p></p><p>Sky News claims that the chancellor, George Osborne, is \"actively investigating\" charging capital gains tax (CGT) when foreign buyers sell UK homes, in a move that will bring their taxation in line with UK citizens.</p><p></p><p>Currently, only UK citizens and residents pay the tax, which is charged on profits made from the sale of any property that is not the owner's main home. Basic rate taxpayers pay 18% of the profits, while higher rate payers hand over 28%.</p><p></p><p>Neither the Treasury or HM Revenue &amp; Customs would comment on the reported change, which Sky suggested would be introduced in December's autumn statement.</p><p></p><p>Recent months have seen a boom in the London property market, with prices rising by about 10% year-on-year and reports of bidding wars for homes in some of the most sought-after neighbourhoods.</p><p></p><p>An influx of overseas investors seeking a safe haven for their money has been blamed for helping to push prices out of the reach of \"normal\" Londoners, with <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2013/oct/20/london-new-york-times-foreign-rich-property\" title=\"Future of London: the New York Times on the foreign rich buying up property\">a writer from the New York Times recently describing the capital's property as \"a global reserve currency for the super elite\"</a>.</p><p></p><p>The UK's property taxation system has been cited as a reason for its appeal, and there have been calls for the government to apply more taxes to the country's richest homebuyers.</p><p></p><p>In 2012's budget, the chancellor introduced a <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/uk/2012/mar/21/budget-stamp-duty-raised\" title=\"Budget 2012: stamp duty on 2m homes raised to 7%\">7% rate of stamp duty for homes costing more than £2m</a> and annual charges for buyers who choose to hold homes in a company rather than as individuals.</p><p></p><p>The Liberal Democrats have repeatedly called for a mansion tax on homes costing more than £2m, but critics suggest this may have more of an impact on domestic homeowners who have owned properties for many years than on overseas buyers.</p><p></p><p>Yolanda Barnes, director of residential research at upmarket estate agency Savills, said bringing CGT rules in line for overseas buyers was \"a sensible move\" and unlikely to deter overseas money from coming to London.</p><p></p><p>\"I don't think it will put many people off at all. It is a relatively modest tax paid only on gains – and if it erodes the case for a mansion tax it could boost the market,\" she said.</p><p></p><p>Barnes said Savills' research suggested that investors from outside the UK were buying properties to let and holding them for the long term.</p><p></p><p>\"People aren't speculating here; they're not flipping properties – foreigners are holding homes for longer than UK sellers,\" she said.</p><p></p><p>Ed Mead of estate agency Douglas &amp; Gordon said the policy would be \"difficult to police\" as the government could struggle to ascertain whether overseas buyers were investors or residing full time in the property.</p><p></p><p>He agreed that it was unlikely to put many people off: \"It's not a draconion move – London will still be a much more attractive and easier place to buy property than many other cities around the world.\"</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/421362915|2013-11-01T16:42:45Z|3aa9675775623743abb5d73638fd746a0d8c51c9 -->",
